<br>
I am wondering that perhaps what they are considering is D-D fusion, this requires much higher temperatures than D-T but all the energy resides in the He and there are no neutrons. (D-D Fusion is “Absolutely” Clean. It is the ultimate nuclear dream)<br>
<br>
The down side, as I see it, is this break-even issue. If they only “Just” break even then this is essentially just another type of electric drive like a VASMIR. Better performance, but possibly not much better because of the constraints of generating and channelling all the electricity necessary to produce the high power radio waves to keep it all hot. In order to get *really* good performance we need to be getting a significant power contribution from the fusion reaction. At least an order of magnitude more than the radio input and preferably several.<br>
<br>
Despite this downside I say good luck to em. I am a big believer of “If you can do it once, you can do it better”<br>
